for so long--too long.

810
01:42:05,165 --> 01:42:07,000
That's how
I lost the feeling...

811
01:42:07,083 --> 01:42:09,125
of my own pleasure.

812
01:42:13,835 --> 01:42:16,626
He did a really
good thing, truly.

813
01:42:16,669 --> 01:42:18,627
Who did a good thing?

814
01:42:18,669 --> 01:42:20,169
Your friend--

815
01:42:20,212 --> 01:42:22,378
your Chinese friend.

816
01:42:22,461 --> 01:42:24,170
He paid off
your brother's debts...

817
01:42:24,171 --> 01:42:26,671
at the opium den.

818
01:42:26,672 --> 01:42:28,630
He also paid for the trip.

819
01:42:28,672 --> 01:42:30,338
He was wonderful--

820
01:42:30,381 --> 01:42:32,506
very discreet, too.

821
01:42:32,548 --> 01:42:35,131
I had underestimated him.

822
01:42:35,173 --> 01:42:37,674
I'm sorry about that.

823
01:42:42,175 --> 01:42:45,134
Do you only see him
for the money?

824
01:42:48,177 --> 01:42:49,635
Yes.

825
01:46:55,363 --> 01:46:58,863
It was when the boat
uttered its first farewell...

826
01:46:58,863 --> 01:47:01,863
and the gangway
had been hauled up...

827
01:47:01,863 --> 01:47:04,863
and the tugs
had started to tow it...

828
01:47:04,864 --> 01:47:07,864
to draw it away
from the land...

829
01:47:07,865 --> 01:47:09,365
that she had wept.

830
01:47:10,866 --> 01:47:13,866
She'd done it
without showing her tears...

831
01:47:13,867 --> 01:47:17,368
without showing her mother
or her little brother...

832
01:47:17,368 --> 01:47:19,368
that she was sad...

833
01:47:19,368 --> 01:47:20,867
without showing anything...

834
01:47:20,868 --> 01:47:24,244
as was the custom
between them.

835
01:48:13,215 --> 01:48:16,257
He was there.

836
01:48:16,340 --> 01:48:19,215
That was him
in the back--

837
01:48:19,258 --> 01:48:22,258
that scarcely visible shape...

838
01:48:22,341 --> 01:48:26,967
that made no movement,
crushed.

839
01:48:33,470 --> 01:48:35,470
She was leaning
on the railing...

840
01:48:35,553 --> 01:48:38,469
like the first time
on the ferry.

841
01:48:38,554 --> 01:48:40,762
She knew
he was watching her.

842
01:48:40,805 --> 01:48:43,221
She was watching him, too.

843
01:49:05,228 --> 01:49:08,352
She couldn't see him anymore,
but she still looked...

844
01:49:08,395 --> 01:49:11,353
towards the shape
of the black car.

845
01:49:21,398 --> 01:49:24,356
In the end,
she didn't see it anymore.

846
01:49:24,399 --> 01:49:26,732
The harbor had faded away...

847
01:49:26,733 --> 01:49:28,733
and then the land.

848
01:49:46,905 --> 01:49:48,071
One night...

849
01:49:48,113 --> 01:49:51,071
during the crossing
of the Indian Ocean...

850
01:49:51,114 --> 01:49:53,739
in the main room
on the big deck...

851
01:49:53,740 --> 01:49:56,239
there had been
a sudden burst...

852
01:49:56,239 --> 01:49:58,239
of a waltz by Chopin.

853
01:50:02,742 --> 01:50:04,741
There wasn't
a breath of wind...

854
01:50:04,742 --> 01:50:06,367
and that night...

855
01:50:06,409 --> 01:50:10,243
the music had spread
all over the black liner...

856
01:50:10,243 --> 01:50:12,243
Like an injunction
from heaven...

857
01:50:12,244 --> 01:50:13,744
related to something unknown...

858
01:50:13,744 --> 01:50:15,744
Like an order from God...

859
01:50:15,745 --> 01:50:18,244
whose meaning
was inscrutable.

860
01:50:40,417 --> 01:50:41,918
She had wept...

861
01:50:41,918 --> 01:50:45,752
because she had thought
of that man from Cholon--

862
01:50:45,752 --> 01:50:47,210
her lover--

863
01:50:47,252 --> 01:50:49,211
and suddenly
she wasn't sure...

864
01:50:49,252 --> 01:50:50,711
of not having loved him...

865
01:50:50,754 --> 01:50:52,753
with a love
she hadn't seen...

866
01:50:52,753 --> 01:50:55,378
because it had lost itself
in the story...

867
01:50:55,421 --> 01:50:57,379
Like water in the sand...

868
01:50:57,422 --> 01:51:00,379
and that she was
rediscovering it now...

869
01:51:00,422 --> 01:51:04,882
in this moment of music
flung across the sea.

870
01:51:28,387 --> 01:51:30,262
Years after the war...

871
01:51:30,304 --> 01:51:32,596
after the marriages,
the children...

872
01:51:32,597 --> 01:51:34,680
the divorces, the books...

873
01:51:34,722 --> 01:51:37,680
he had come to Paris
with his wife.

874
01:51:37,723 --> 01:51:39,389
He had phoned her.

875
01:51:41,724 --> 01:51:43,183
He was intimidated.

876
01:51:43,225 --> 01:51:45,225
His voice trembled...

877
01:51:45,267 --> 01:51:46,725
and with the trembling...

878
01:51:46,767 --> 01:51:50,267
it had found
the accent of China again.

879
01:51:50,309 --> 01:51:52,684
He knew she'd
begun writing books.

880
01:51:52,727 --> 01:51:56,101
He had also heard about
the younger brother's death.

881
01:51:56,144 --> 01:51:58,603
He had been sad for her...

882
01:51:58,645 --> 01:52:02,604
and then he hadn't known
what to tell her...

883
01:52:02,646 --> 01:52:05,103
and then he'd told her--

884
01:52:05,146 --> 01:52:07,938
he had told her
that it was as before...

885
01:52:07,980 --> 01:52:10,605
that he still loved her...

886
01:52:10,648 --> 01:52:13,107
that he would never
stop loving her...

887
01:52:13,149 --> 01:52:16,149
that he would love her
until his death.

